Analysis of Ford GoBike System Data¶

by oooo rrrr¶

Investigation Overview¶

The most interesting part is to identify which stations are most overwhelmed with users and expreincing low or high number of bike-returns so that more investment and bike-transportation will be channeled. Which particular bikes were overused and need some repairment. And what day hours and weekdays bike-renting is most frequent, in what geo-positions bike-sharing business is most popular. Bike-riding popularity among genders and users as well as age groups. Furthermore, we can explore which station-to-station jurneys are most lucrative.

Dataset Overview¶

In the dataset we have 183215 bike-lending records, which spans 28 days of February in 2019, in our dataset after preliminary cleaning, and 5 variables are categorical and 11 variables are numeric. Some columns that have unproper formats have been corrected. The structure is very well, except for member_gender which has some missing values and we can explore univariate, bivariate and multivariate relationships between bike trip duration, start time, geo-coordinates, start and end stations, user type, gender and their age. From the users' birth year we can calculate their age.

Distribution of the bike trip durations¶

Trip duration has a long-tailed distribution, with a lot of bike trips on the short duration end, and few on the long duration end. When plotted on a log-scale, the trip duration distribution looks roughly bell-shaped, with longest durations around 500 seconds (8.3 minutes).

In [5]:
log_binsize = 0.015
bins = 10 ** np.arange(1, np.log10(df['duration_sec'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.xlabel('Duration (seconds)')
plt.title('Distribution of the bike trip durations')
plt.show()

Distribution of what day hours and weekdays bike-renting is most frequent¶

Most bike trips occurs during the 9th and 18th hour of the day which are between 8.00 a.m. and 9 a.m. and between 17.00 p.m. and 18 p.m. respectively. During daytime bike trip frequencies are roughly equal while midtime it decreases significantly. Most popular week day for bike trips is Thursday while other weekdays it is slightly lower. However on weekends bike trips are twice as lower as weekdays.

Trip popularity among age groups¶

For age groups, in order to calculate bike trip popularity among age groups we will create another column named "age_groups" with 5 years intervals in our dataset. Those who are in their the 20s and 30s are predominantly active in bike tripping.

In [8]:
#create age group column and plot bike trip distribution for age groups:
def spot_the_age_group(x):
    age = 2019 - x
    for i in np.arange(0, 110, 10):
        if (age >= i) and (age < i+10):
            return f'{i}s'

df['age_group'] = df['member_birth_year'].apply(spot_the_age_group)
df_age_groups = df['age_group'].value_counts().sort_index()
age_list = list(df_age_groups.index)
age_list = age_list[1:] + age_list[:1]
df_age_groups = df_age_groups.reindex(age_list)

#then we will plot the bike trip distribution among age groups
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.bar(x=df_age_groups.index, 
        height= df_age_groups)
plt.xlabel('Age groups')
plt.title('Bike trip popularity among age groups')
plt.show()

Top and outsider 20 stations with the number of bikes are inflowing and outflowing¶

We can say that stations 3, 6, 5, 15, 16, 21, 22, 30, 58, 67 and 81 are the top 11 stations that had most bike outflows and inflows, with 58 and 67 are championing in these regards respectively. The marketing department should pay an attention to this fact. In the meantime, the stations 67, 21, 15, 6, 44, 30, 3, 88, 182 are the top 9 stations that had stockpiled excess bikes and the stations 243, 253, 22, 71, 343, 256, 84, 81, 52 are the top 9 stations that experieced the shortage of bikes, with 67 and 243 extremelely high. Excess bikes shuold be transported to the stations falling short of enough bikes.

#find how many bikes each station had lended altogether
start_stations = df.start_station_id.value_counts()
start_stations = pd.DataFrame(start_stations).reset_index().rename(columns={'index':'station_id','start_station_id':'bike_outflows'})

#find how many bikes each station had received altogether
end_stations = df.end_station_id.value_counts()
end_stations = pd.DataFrame(end_stations).reset_index().rename(columns={'index':'station_id','end_station_id':'bike_inflows'})

#join the two dataframes above:
df_bike_inflow_outflow = start_stations.set_index('station_id').join(end_stations.set_index('station_id'), how='outer')
df_bike_inflow_outflow['net_bike_inflows'] = df_bike_inflow_outflow['bike_inflows'] - df_bike_inflow_outflow['bike_outflows']
df_bike_inflow_outflow.reset_index(inplace=True)

#plot the 20 receiver, lender stations as well as the top 20 stations that are experiecing bike deficits or proficits 
#at the end of the period.
sb.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=4, figsize = [8,8], tight_layout=True)
data1=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'bike_outflows']].sort_values(by=['bike_outflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data2=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['bike_inflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data3=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'net_bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['net_bike_inflows'], ascending=False).head(20)
data4=df_bike_inflow_outflow[['station_id', 'net_bike_inflows']].sort_values(by=['net_bike_inflows'], ascending=True).head(20)

default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
red = sb.color_palette()[3]
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="bike_outflows", data=data1, ax=ax[0], order=data1['station_id'], color=default_color)
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="bike_inflows", data=data2, ax=ax[1], order=data2['station_id'], color=default_color)
sb.barplot(x="station_id", y="net_bike_inflows", data=data3, ax=ax[2], order=data3['station_id'], color=default_color)

ax[0].set_title('The top 20 stations with bike inflow numbers')
ax[1].set_title('The top 20 stations with bike outflow numbers')
ax[2].set_title('The top 20 stations with net bike inflow numbers')
ax[3].set_title('The most outsider 20 stations with net zero bike inflow numbers')
plt.show()

Overall durations per age group¶

People who are in their 30s and 20s had went for bike trips for way longer durations than other age groups. And average bike trip duration per user in groups does not vary very much, except for those in their 80s and 90s being slightly lower.

In [11]:
# calculate overall durations per age group
df_overall_duration_per_agegroup = df[['age_group', 'duration_sec']].groupby('age_group').sum().reset_index()
df_overall_duration_per_agegroup.sort_values(by='duration_sec', ascending=False, inplace=True)
df_overall_duration_per_agegroup.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_overall_duration_per_agegroup['duration_sec'] = df_overall_duration_per_agegroup['duration_sec'].apply(lambda x: x/3600)
df_overall_duration_per_agegroup.rename(columns={'duration_sec':'duration_hours'}, inplace=True)
data =df_overall_duration_per_agegroup

default_color = sb.color_palette()[9]
sb.set(rc = {'figure.figsize':(10,5)})
sb.barplot(x="age_group", y="duration_hours", data=data, color=default_color)
plt.title('Overall durations per age group')
plt.show()

Mapping the stations according to their geopositions¶

When we did bivariate exploration, we found that the stations are located cluster-like in three major areas. Now we will name the most north-western one, the most north-eastern one and the most south-eastern one A, B and C areas respectively. Accordingly, we will analyse end-of-the-period shortages and abundances of bikes and compare them on the map.

In all the three areas overall shortages and ubundancies of bikes are fairly balanced. Transportation can be done inside each area.
